he three places called Bradshaw in Lancashire, Yorkshire, and Derbyshire, from Old English <i>brād</i> ‘broad’ + <i>sceaga</i> ‘thicket’."],"variants":[{"name":"Brayshaw","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Bradshaw  , reflecting the local Yorkshire pronunciation."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]},{"name":"Leigh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Lee  , from an alternative spelling of the surname. As a girl's name it is frequently an element of compound names such as <i>Abbie-Leigh</i>, <i>Jodie-Leigh,</i> and <i>Katie-Leigh</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":20,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":33,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":42,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":87,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger Leigh Bradshaw was born in 1295, in Leigh, Lancashire, England, his father, John Bradshaw, was 21 and his mother, Lady Holcroft Cheshire De Holcroft, was 25. He married Miss Osbaldeston-Bradhaigh in 1336, in Haigh, Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died on 27 August 1382, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 87."},"et":{"1310–27 AUG 1382":"1295–27. august 1382","1295–1382":"1295–1382","1315–1361":"1315–1361","1345–1417":"1345–1417","1355–1383":"1355–1383","1275–1337":"1275–1337","1270–1349":"1270–1349","27 AUG 1382":"27. august 1382","1275":"1275","1361":"1361","1383":"1383","1295":"1295","1382":"1382","1270":"1270","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1336":"1336","1345":"1345","1355":"1355","1310":"1295","1453":"1453","about 1345":"umbes 1345","1417":"1417","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Blackrod, Lancashire, England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdo